[[fr:AideSurInternet]]

If you are looking for information about Emacs, the first place to look is Emacs itself.  See SelfDocumentation.

A lot of information can be found online:

* EmacsNewsgroups, EmacsMailingLists, EmacsForums.
* The EmacsLispList -- http://www.anc.ed.ac.uk/~stephen/emacs/ell.html.
* EmacsFaq -- Frequently asked questions of Emacs.
* The NT Emacs FAQ -- http://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/windows/.
* The annotated EmacsLispReference online, and EmacsLispIntro for beginners.
* Tutorial Collection by KaiGrossjohann -- ftp://ftp.is.informatik.uni-duisburg.de/pub/src/emacs/tutorials/tutorials_toc.html.
* Emacs references and faqs by JariAalto -- http://www.nongnu.org/emacs-tiny-tools/resources/index.html.
* Emacs KeybindingGuide by JariAalto.
* Why Emacs?  A tour of Emacs from a newbie's perspective, by CharlesSebold -- http://www.livingtorah.org/~csebold/emacs/why.phtml. [That link seems to be broken.]
* [http://web.mit.edu/olh/Emacs/Emacs.html MIT's Emacs Introduction]
* [http://jeremy.zawodny.com/emacs/emacs.html Emacs Beginner's HOWTO]
* The [http://en.chainki.org/index.php?title=Emacs_(Computers/Open_Source/Software/Editors)
Emacs pages on the Chainki wiki]. This is a general purpose wiki of links
based on the [http://dmoz.org Open Directory Project] but reworked into wiki format.
* PlanetEmacsen -- An aggregation of the blogs of Emacs users.
* [http://www.emacsblog.org/ M-x all-things-emacs] -- A place for both Emacs
n00bs and hax0rz to gain a little more out of Emacs.
* ElispCookbook -- This page contains snippets of code that demonstrate basic
elisp programming operations in the spirit of the o'reilly cookbook series of
books.
* [http://web.psung.name/emacs/ Being Productive With Emacs] by Phil Sung
** [http://web.psung.name/emacs/2009/part1.html Introduction]: why Emacs?; overview of editing commands; macros; major and minor modes.
** [http://web.psung.name/emacs/2009/part2.html Emacs lisp]: rebinding keys; hooks; extending Emacs with your own commands.
** Older stuff - ''Seems to have moved''
*** [http://web.psung.name/emacs/2007/emacs-slides-1.pdf
Being Productive With Emacs - Part 1 (PDF)] -- ''"Emacs is the extensible,
customizable, selfdocumenting realtime display editor."''
It's a good Emacs tutorial.
(Working quickly in Emacs; modes; macros; useful features; how to learn more.)
*** [http://web.psung.name/emacs/2007/emacs-slides-2.pdf
Being Productive With Emacs - Part 2 (PDF)] -- Emacs Lisp for implementation,
for customization and for extending Emacs.
(Foundations of Emacs Lisp; keybindings, variables, hooks; the InitFile;
defining interactive functions.)
*** [http://web.psung.name/emacs/2007/emacs-slides-3.pdf
Being Productive With Emacs - Part 3 (PDF)] -- Extending Emacs.
(Interactive arguments; advice; defining new modes.)
* [http://emacs.dreamwidth.org/ emacs community on Dreamwidth]
* [http://steve-yegge.blogspot.com/2006/06/shiny-and-new-emacs-22.html
Stevey's Blog Rants: Shiny and New: Emacs 22] -- It has good tips about Emacs,
specially about <code>replace-regexp</code> use.
* IBM Developer Works series on the ''Emacs Editing Environment''.  '''Registration required.'''
** [http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/edu/au-dw-au-emacs1-i.html Part 1: Learn the basics of Emacs].
** [http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/edu/au-dw-au-emacs2-i.html Part 2: Learn the essential modes and editing features of Emacs].
** [http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/edu/au-dw-au-emacs3-i.html Part 3: Advanced Emacs text operations].
** [http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/edu/au-dw-au-emacs4-i.html Part 4: Options, registers, and bookmarks].
** [http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/edu/au-dw-au-emacs5-i.html Part 5: Shape your Emacs view].
** [http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/edu/au-dw-au-emacs6-i.html Part 6: Customize your Emacs world].
** [http://www-128.ibm.com/developerworks/edu/au-dw-au-emacs7-i.html Part 7: Let Emacs help you out].
* [http://www.cb1.com/~john/computing/emacs/beyond-tutorial.html Beyond the tutorial] -- Consise summary of [[key]]s, [[command]]s, terminology, [[regexp]] syntax....

